[It is odd that there is no mention of the symptoms for this case, nor the basis for suspecting a hantavirus infection or leptospirosis. As with the report above, the reports of hantavirus infections that ProMED receives very seldom mention which hantavirus is the etiologic agent of the cases. Cases of hantavirus infection have been reported from various parts of Argentina over recent years. As noted in ProMED-mail archive no. 20110430.1348, several endemic hantaviruses have been associated with human infection in Argentina: Andes virus (western Argentina, in the long-tailed pygmy rice rat host, _Oligoryzomys longicaudatus_); related Andes-like viruses Hu39694 (in central Argentina; rodent host unknown); Lechiguana (in central Argentina in the yellow pygmy rice rat _O. flavescens_); Oran (in northwestern Argentina in _O. longicaudatus_); and Bermejo (western Argentina in _O. flavescens_). Without laboratory confirmation, it is not possible to say with certainty which hantavirus was involved in this Entre Rios province case. Although Andes virus seems unlikely, Seoul virus with the brown rat (_Rattus norvegicus_) host is another possibility. ProMED would appreciate receiving further information coming from the autopsy and laboratory test results.

Although mice and rats were mentioned as possible rodent hosts in the report above, the rodent host of the suspected hantavirus endemic in this area has not been reported above.

Maps of Argentina: http://www.zonu.com/argentina_maps/Argentina_Regions_Map_2.htm and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5557055,51189. - Mod.TY]
